@label noether
   \setwidth{78}

   \textbf{Theorem} (Noether, field-theory version).
   \textit{Let $\mathcal{L}(\phi^a, \partial_\mu \phi^a, x^\mu)$ be a
   Lagrangian density depending on $N$ fields $\phi^a$ ($a = 1, \ldots, N$)
   and their first derivatives, and let the action be}

   $$S[\phi] = \int d^4x\; \mathcal{L}(\phi^a, \partial_\mu \phi^a, x^\mu) \tag{1}$$

   \textit{Suppose $S$ is invariant — up to a total divergence — under a
   continuous one-parameter family of field transformations parametrised by
   $\epsilon$:}

   $$\phi^a(x) \;\longmapsto\; \phi^a(x) + \epsilon\,\Delta\phi^a(x),
   \qquad x^\mu \;\longmapsto\; x^\mu + \epsilon\,\xi^\mu(x) \tag{2}$$

   \textit{Then there exists a conserved current $j^\mu(x)$ satisfying}

   $$\boxed{\partial_\mu j^\mu = 0} \tag{N}$$

   \textit{and a corresponding conserved charge}

   $$Q \coloneqq \int_{\Sigma} d^3x\; j^0(x), \qquad \frac{dQ}{dt} = 0 \tag{3}$$

   \textit{where $\Sigma$ is any spacelike hypersurface.}

   \textbf{Proof.}

   \textbf{Step 1: Variation of the action.}
   Under the transformation (2), the field variation at fixed spacetime
   point $x$ is

   $$\delta_\epsilon \phi^a \coloneqq \epsilon\!\left(
   \Delta\phi^a - \xi^\mu \partial_\mu \phi^a\right)
   \eqqcolon \epsilon\,\bar{\Delta}\phi^a \tag{4}$$

   where $\bar{\Delta}\phi^a$ is the \textit{internal} variation — the
   change in the field value at a fixed label point. The corresponding
   variation of the Lagrangian density is:

   $$\delta_\epsilon \mathcal{L} = \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial \phi^a}
   \,\bar{\Delta}\phi^a
   + \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu \phi^a)}
   \,\partial_\mu(\bar{\Delta}\phi^a)
   + \xi^\mu \partial_\mu \mathcal{L} \tag{5}$$

   \textbf{Step 2: Using the Euler-Lagrange equations.}
   On-shell — i.e.\ for fields satisfying the field equations — the
   Euler-Lagrange equations hold for each field $\phi^a$:

   $$\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial \phi^a}
   - \partial_\mu \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu \phi^a)}
   = 0 \tag{EL}$$

   We use (EL) to rewrite the first term in (5). Adding and subtracting
   $\partial_\mu\!\left(\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu
   \phi^a)}\right)\bar{\Delta}\phi^a$:

   $$\aligned{
   \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial \phi^a}\,\bar{\Delta}\phi^a
   + \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu \phi^a)}
     \,\partial_\mu(\bar{\Delta}\phi^a)
   &= \partial_\mu\!\left[
      \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu \phi^a)}
      \,\bar{\Delta}\phi^a\right] \\
   &\quad + \underbrace{\left[
      \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial \phi^a}
      - \partial_\mu\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu \phi^a)}
      \right]}_{\displaystyle =\;0\;\text{(EL)}}\!\bar{\Delta}\phi^a
   } \tag{6}$$

   The underbraced term vanishes on-shell. Substituting back into (5):

   $$\delta_\epsilon \mathcal{L}
   = \partial_\mu\!\left[
     \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu \phi^a)}
     \,\bar{\Delta}\phi^a\right]
   + \xi^\mu \partial_\mu \mathcal{L} \tag{7}$$

   \textbf{Step 3: The symmetry condition.}
   By assumption, the transformation (2) is a symmetry: $S$ is invariant
   up to a total divergence, meaning

   $$\delta_\epsilon \mathcal{L} = \epsilon\,\partial_\mu K^\mu(x) \tag{8}$$

   for some current $K^\mu$ (which vanishes for strict symmetries).
   Dividing by $\epsilon$ and combining (7) and (8):

   $$\partial_\mu\!\left[
     \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu \phi^a)}
     \,\bar{\Delta}\phi^a
     + \xi^\mu \mathcal{L} - K^\mu
   \right] = 0 \tag{9}$$

   \textbf{Step 4: The Noether current.}
   Equation (9) is a conservation law $\partial_\mu j^\mu = 0$ with

   $$j^\mu \coloneqq \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu \phi^a)}
   \,\bar{\Delta}\phi^a
   + \xi^\mu \mathcal{L} - K^\mu \tag{10}$$

   Substituting back the definition $\bar{\Delta}\phi^a = \Delta\phi^a -
   \xi^\nu \partial_\nu \phi^a$ from (4):

   $$\boxed{j^\mu = \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu \phi^a)}
   \!\left(\Delta\phi^a - \xi^\nu \partial_\nu \phi^a\right)
   + \xi^\mu \mathcal{L} - K^\mu} \tag{11}$$

   This is the \textbf{Noether current}.

   \textbf{Step 5: The conserved charge.}
   Integrating $\partial_\mu j^\mu = 0$ over a spacetime volume $V$
   bounded by two spacelike slices $\Sigma_{t_1}$ and $\Sigma_{t_2}$,
   and applying the divergence theorem:

   $$\aligned{
   0 &= \int_V d^4x\; \partial_\mu j^\mu \\
     &= \int_{\Sigma_{t_2}} d^3x\; j^0
      - \int_{\Sigma_{t_1}} d^3x\; j^0
      + \oint_{\partial V_\text{spatial}} j^i \, dS_i
   } \tag{12}$$

   Assuming the fields fall off sufficiently fast at spatial infinity so
   that the boundary term vanishes, we obtain

   $$\frac{d}{dt} \int_\Sigma d^3x\; j^0(x) = 0 \tag{13}$$

   so the charge $Q \coloneqq \int_\Sigma d^3x\; j^0$ is conserved. $\square$

   \vskip{1}

   \textbf{Remark 1} (Internal symmetry: $U(1)$ example).
   \textit{Consider a complex scalar field $\psi$ with Lagrangian
   $\mathcal{L} = |\partial_\mu \psi|^2 - m^2|\psi|^2$. The transformation
   $\psi \mapsto e^{i\epsilon}\psi$ is a $U(1)$ symmetry with $\xi^\mu = 0$
   and $\Delta\psi = i\psi$. The Noether current is}

   $$j^\mu = i\!\left[\psi^* \partial^\mu\psi - (\partial^\mu\psi^*)\psi\right]
   \tag{14}$$

   \textit{and the conserved charge is the total electric charge
   $Q = \int d^3x\; j^0$. This is the prototype for all gauge theories.}

   \textbf{Remark 2} (Spacetime translation: energy-momentum tensor).
   For the spacetime translation $x^\mu \to x^\mu + \epsilon^\mu$ we have
   $\xi^\mu = \delta^\mu_\nu$ (for translation in direction $\nu$) and
   $\Delta\phi^a = 0$, $K^\mu = 0$. The four conserved currents (one per
   direction $\nu$) are assembled into the \textbf{energy-momentum tensor}:

   $$T^\mu{}_\nu \coloneqq
   \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu \phi^a)}\,\partial_\nu \phi^a
   - \delta^\mu_\nu\,\mathcal{L} \tag{15}$$

   satisfying $\partial_\mu T^\mu{}_\nu = 0$. The four conserved charges are

   $$P^\nu = \int_\Sigma d^3x\; T^{0\nu} \tag{16}$$

   — the total energy ($\nu = 0$) and spatial momentum ($\nu = 1, 2, 3$)
   of the field configuration.

   \textbf{Remark 3} (Angular momentum and Lorentz invariance).
   For Lorentz boosts and rotations $x^\mu \to x^\mu +
   \omega^\mu{}_\nu x^\nu$ (with $\omega_{\mu\nu}$ antisymmetric), the
   Noether procedure yields the \textbf{angular momentum tensor}

   $$M^{\mu\nu\rho} \coloneqq x^\nu T^{\mu\rho} - x^\rho T^{\mu\nu}
   + \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_\mu \phi^a)}
   \,(S^{\nu\rho})^a{}_b\,\phi^b \tag{17}$$

   where $(S^{\nu\rho})^a{}_b$ are the spin matrices of the field in
   representation $a$. The last term is the intrinsic spin contribution,
   absent for scalar fields.

   \textbf{Remark 4} (Quantum version).
   \textit{In canonical quantisation, $Q$ becomes an operator. If the
   vacuum is invariant, $Q|0\rangle = 0$, then the symmetry is realised in
   the Wigner-Weyl mode and the spectrum organises into multiplets of the
   symmetry group. If $Q|0\rangle \neq 0$, the symmetry is spontaneously
   broken — the Goldstone theorem then guarantees a massless scalar
   particle for each broken generator, with $\partial_\mu j^\mu = 0$
   holding as an operator equation.}
@end

